{{Infobox MP | honorific-prefix = | name = Steve Georganas | honorific-suffix = | image = | constituency_MP = [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] | parliament = Australian | majority = | predecessor = [[Christine Gallus]] | successor = | term_start = 9 October 2004 | term_end = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1959|6|13}} | birth_place = [[Adelaide, South Australia]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Australia]]n | spouse = | party = [[Australian Labor Party]] | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | occupation = Underwriter, advisor | profession = | religion = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Steven "Steve" Georganas''' (born 13 June 1959), [[Australia]]n politician, is the [[Australian Labor Party]] representative for the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] seat of [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] in [[South Australia]] since the [[Australian federal election, 2004|2004 federal election]].
Georganas was born in [[Adelaide]] of [[Greece|Greek]] parents. He gained a Business Studies Certificate at a [[TAFE]] college and worked as an underwriter and in financial services. Georganas has been involved in numerous community organizations, including as president of his local Lions club, and as a board member of the Adelaide [[Greek culture|Greek]] Festival "[[Glendi]]".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.alp.org.au/federal-government/labor-people/steve-georganas |title=Steve Georganas |work=ALP.org.au |publisher=Australian Labor Party |accessdate=24 November 2011}}</ref> Georganas was a ministerial adviser from 2002 to 2004 for South Australian government minister [[Jay Weatherill]].
Georganas contested [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] at the [[Australian federal election, 1998|1998 election]] and the [[Australian federal election, 2001|2001 election]] before winning it at the [[Australian federal election, 2004|2004 election]], replacing the retiring incumbent, [[Christine Gallus]] from the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]]. Georganas defeated Liberal candidate [[Simon Birmingham]] by only 108 votes, or by 0.06 percent of the two-party vote. He easily retained the seat picking up a five percent two-party swing when his party won government at the [[Australian federal election, 2007|2007 election]].
